## Human and Societal Impact

### Casualties and Destruction

The invasion resulted in significant military and civilian casualties. German forces suffered approximately 16,343 killed and 30,300 wounded, while Polish military casualties were around 66,000 dead and 133,700 wounded, with an additional 694,000 captured. The civilian population endured brutal repression, with an estimated two million ethnic Poles killed during the occupation by both Nazi Germany and the Soviet Union ([Treehozz](https://treehozz.com/why-was-germanys-invasion-of-poland-important)).

### Concentration Camps and the Holocaust

Poland became the epicenter of Nazi concentration and extermination camps, including Auschwitz, Treblinka, and Sobibor. These camps were instrumental in the Holocaust, where millions of Jews, along with other persecuted groups, were systematically murdered. The invasion thus not only triggered a military conflict but also precipitated one of history’s gravest humanitarian catastrophes ([Warbleton Council](https://warbletoncouncil.org/invasion-alemana-de-polonia-14043)).

